    "decision_handoff_body": "\n# Decision summary\n\nJavokhir Sindarov is very likely to win the 2026 FIDE Candidates Tournament, but the best post-synthesis estimate is still slightly below the 95.05% market because the strongest independently checked evidence supports an overwhelming late lead rather than a fully settled official result.\n\n## Why this may matter now\n\nMarket-implied probability is 0.9505. My syndicated range is 0.89 to 0.94. That is still a strong yes view, but the edge versus market is marginal-to-negative rather than actionable. The market may be a touch rich because it is pricing a near-converted lead almost like an already-declared win.\n\n## Shift versus swarm baseline\n\nThis is not a large move from the swarm-implied center around 0.91. I stay close to it because the strongest lanes were broadly right: the visible state is not generic player-strength optimism but a specific late-event lead. I lean slightly toward the upper half of the swarm because the synthesis-stage check supported the key catalyst-hunter claim that Sindarov was two points clear and at least playoff-secured. I do not move up to market because direct official standings verification remained imperfect.\n\n## Edge verification status\n\nIndependent verification was medium, not high. What was checked well enough: multiple persona lanes converged on the same late-state picture; the raw findings consistently cited FIDE as the governing source; and the synthesis-stage fetch of Chess.com news successfully surfaced text stating Sindarov was guaranteed at least a playoff and two points clear with two rounds to go. What remained weak: web search failed, one FIDE fetch landed on an unrelated page, and I did not directly capture a clean official FIDE standings/clinch page. That is enough to reject the most bearish 0.58-style view, but not enough to fully endorse 95%+ certainty.\n\n## Compression toward market\n\nNo. The final range did not compress toward the market; if anything, it stayed modestly below it. Verification was strong enough to support the core late-stage bullish thesis, but not strong enough to eliminate all residual tail risk. So the synthesis preserved the swarm's below-market posture rather than reverting upward.\n\n## Timing and catalyst posture\n\nThe next critical checkpoint is round 13, especially Sindarov vs Giri. That appears to be the only remaining clearly material catalyst. If Sindarov avoids defeat, probability should widen toward near-certainty; if he loses, the market should compress sharply. Waiting until after round 13 is more likely to improve decision quality than acting on tiny pre-round mispricings.\n\n## Key blockers\n\nMain blockers are modest rather than fatal: no clean official FIDE standings/clinch page was directly captured, and the tournament was still live. There is no major contract blocker; the main issue is calibration at extreme probability, not source-of-truth confusion.\n\n## Best countercase\n\nThe best countercase came from risk-manager, with some support from base-rate: the 95% price may be overconfident if it relies on inferred late-state context not directly verified from official standings, and one bad result against Giri could quickly reopen the event. That countercase survived synthesis, but only as a tail-risk/pricing caution, not as the mainline forecast.\n\n## What would change the view\n\nAn official FIDE standings or round report showing Sindarov has effectively clinched would push me toward or even above the current market. A round-13 loss, an official correction to the standings interpretation, or any fair-play/administrative complication would move me down materially. Even a draw could matter depending on exact remaining pairings and tiebreak math.\n\n## Recommended next action\n\nWait for official FIDE reporting after round 13. If Sindarov avoids defeat, request decision-maker review with a near-certainty update. If he loses, rerun at least catalyst-hunter and risk-manager immediately with exact official standings and playoff implications.\n\n## Verification impact\n\nYes, synthesis-stage verification was used, though bounded. Cross-lane comparison materially weakened the most bearish persona by showing that its missing-context objection was partially answered elsewhere. It also exposed a consistent provenance weakness across even the bullish lanes: everyone ultimately wanted a cleaner official standings capture than the run achieved.\n",
